	<div class=3D"single__body___N62Sv">
		<div class=3D"single__content___jOVhr">
			<div class=3D"rich-text rich-text--with-sidebar single__rich-text___DT62=
t" data-component=3D"video-embed">
			=09
<p>In everyday life, we often use the words =E2=80=9Cmass=E2=80=9D and =E2=
=80=9Cweight=E2=80=9D as if they=E2=80=99re the same. But in science, it=E2=
=80=99s important to be precise. <a href=3D"https://www.sciencenewsforstude=
nts.org/article/scientists-say-mass" rel=3D"noopener">Mass</a> and weight a=
re both measurements that describe heaviness, but they actually mean very d=
ifferent things. Let=E2=80=99s be specific!</p>



<p><strong>Mass</strong> is a measurement of the amount of matter in some o=
bject. It depends only on what type of <a href=3D"https://www.sciencenewsfo=
rstudents.org/article/scientists-say-atom" rel=3D"noopener">atoms</a> the o=
bject is made of, and how many atoms there are. Mass is traditionally measu=
red in kilograms (kg). A pineapple or a wooden baseball bat each have a mas=
s of about 1 kilogram. &nbsp;</p>



<p>If you were to measure out 1 kilogram of steel and 1 kilogram of feather=
s, they would each have the same mass. But their volumes would differ. You=
=E2=80=99d need a far bigger volume of feathers because most of the element=
s they=E2=80=99re made from are lighter than those in steel. It takes more =
of those atoms to build up the same mass =E2=80=94 which takes up more spac=
e.</p>



<section class=3D"newsletter-signup__wrapper___lZ0W1 wp-block-house-ads wp-=
block-newsletter-signup">
=09
<iframe loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"cid:frame-02F0C7FEFB7984BA19EFE8388EA6BC36@=
mhtml.blink" width=3D"100%" height=3D"224" frameborder=3D"0" scrolling=3D"n=
o" data-gtm-yt-inspected-49=3D"true" data-gtm-yt-inspected-54=3D"true"></if=
rame>
</section>



<p>People in the United States rarely describe objects using kilograms in d=
aily life. Scientists and doctors use this term because it is the standard =
unit of mass in the metric system. (A standard unit is a definition that al=
l scientists agree on.) &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>You can change an object=E2=80=99s mass by removing some of its parts. W=
hen you take books out of your backpack at the end of a school day, you=E2=
=80=99ve decreased the backpack=E2=80=99s mass. Mass can also change by add=
ing more matter. When a child grows, their body is building longer bones an=
d bigger organs. The child=E2=80=99s mass will increase because they are tr=
ansforming food energy into matter for their body.</p>



<p>It=E2=80=99s important to know that mass doesn=E2=80=99t change by varyi=
ng its shape, location or size. Your body=E2=80=99s mass is the same when y=
ou=E2=80=99re curled up on the sofa or when you stretch as high as you can.=
 And it=E2=80=99s the same when you=E2=80=99re at home or at the beach or a=
t school! But your mass is a little bit more after you=E2=80=99ve eaten bre=
akfast, compared with when you first wake up in the morning. Mass is a fund=
amental measurement of how much matter an object contains.</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-image aligncenter size-full"><img loading=3D"lazy=
" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1030" height=3D"1030" src=3D"https://www.scie=
ncenewsforstudents.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/1030_mass_vs_weight_moon.=
jpg" alt=3D"A photo of astronaut John Young bouncing across the moon. The p=
hoto shows him mid-bounce, suspended in the air." class=3D"wp-image-3110670=
"><figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption"><span class=3D"caption wp-captio=
n-3110670">Astronaut John Young bounded across the lunar surface during the=
 Apollo 16 mission in April 1972. His space suit more than doubled Young=E2=
=80=99s mass. The moon=E2=80=99s gravity is so weak, however, that he could=
 still jump easily.</span><span class=3D"credit wp-credit-3110670">NASA</sp=
an></figcaption></figure>



<p><strong>Weight</strong> is a measurement of the gravitational force on a=
n object. It not only depends on the object=E2=80=99s mass, but also on its=
 location. Therefore, weight is actually a measure of force. In the United =
States, most people measure weight in pounds.</p>



<p>Let=E2=80=99s say that your body has a mass of 40 kilograms. Your mass i=
s 40 kilograms on Earth, on the moon, on Jupiter =E2=80=94 and even floatin=
g inside the International Space Station. Your mass is 40 kilograms no matt=
er where you are. But your weight differs from place to place because of di=
fferences in how hard <a href=3D"https://www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/art=
icle/scientists-say-gravity" rel=3D"noopener">gravity</a> at each site pull=
s on you. On Earth=E2=80=99s surface, 1 kilogram of mass is equivalent to 2=
.2 pounds of weight. So your 40-kilogram mass on Earth would weigh 40 x 2.2=
 =E2=80=94 or 88 pounds.</p>



<aside class=3D"wp-block-sciencenews-inline-related-post alignleft"><h4><a =
href=3D"https://www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/article/explainer-gravity-an=
d-microgravity" rel=3D"noopener">Explainer: Gravity and microgravity</a></h=
4></aside>





<p>Language can get tricky here. Scientifically, you shouldn=E2=80=99t say,=
 =E2=80=9CMy doctor measured my weight as 40 kilograms,=E2=80=9D because <e=
m>weight</em> isn=E2=80=99t the same as mass. It would be similarly incorre=
ct to say, =E2=80=9CMy doctor measured my mass as 88 pounds.=E2=80=9D Howev=
er, since we all experience the same strength of Earth=E2=80=99s gravity on=
 our mass, in casual language we often use mass and weight interchangeably.=
 In much the same way, most people feel comfortable describing mass in poun=
ds and weight in kilograms.</p>



<p>To avoid this confusion, scientists use a standard unit for force. It=E2=
=80=99s called the newton (in honor of Isaac Newton). On Earth, 100 newtons=
 of weight (a force) is equal to about 22 pounds. This is a measure of how =
hard Earth=E2=80=99s gravity pulls on a mass of about 10 kilograms.</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Mass and weight are proportiona<strong>l</st=
rong></h4>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-image alignright size-large"><img loading=3D"lazy=
" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"291" height=3D"450" src=3D"https://www.scienc=
enewsforstudents.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/680_mass_vs_weight_launch-2=
91x450.jpg" alt=3D"a photo of a nighttime launch of the space shuttle Disco=
very. The back of the shuttle is lit up by the exhaust from the rockets " c=
lass=3D"wp-image-3110671"><figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption"><span cl=
ass=3D"caption wp-caption-3110671">This photo of a nighttime launch of a sp=
ace shuttle shows how big its engines and rocket boosters are. Rockets need=
 much more power in the first few minutes after launch than they do later.<=
/span><span class=3D"credit wp-credit-3110671">NASA</span></figcaption></fi=
gure>



<p>As the mass of something rises or falls, its weight will change in the s=
ame way. And if the gravitational force on something rises or falls, its we=
ight will also. In short, the mass of something rarely changes, but there a=
re multiple ways its weight can change. &nbsp;</p>



<p>The gravity you=E2=80=99d feel on the surface of a planet depends on its=
 density. We say that Earth has the gravitational force of one =E2=80=9CG.=
=E2=80=9D The moon is much smaller and less dense than Earth. Its gravity i=
s one-sixth G. Although Jupiter is much, much bigger than Earth, it=E2=80=
=99s not very dense. So Jupiter=E2=80=99s gravity is 2.5 G.</p>



<p>If your mass is 40 kilograms on Earth, your 88-pound weight would drop t=
o 15 pounds on the moon. On Jupiter, you=E2=80=99d weigh 220 pounds. On the=
 International Space Station, floating in <a href=3D"https://www.sciencenew=
sforstudents.org/article/scientists-say-orbit" rel=3D"noopener">orbit</a>, =
your <a href=3D"https://www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/article/scientists-s=
ay-microgravity" rel=3D"noopener">weight would be zero</a>. But your mass w=
ould stay the same =E2=80=94 40 kg =E2=80=94 in all of these places. For th=
at reason, mass is a fundamental property of matter and weight is not.</p>



<p>Rocket launches offer an interesting example of how mass and weight rela=
te. At launch, the rocket is full of fuel, so its mass is greatest. At Eart=
h=E2=80=99s surface, it also feels the maximum pull of gravity. So its weig=
ht is heaviest. A few minutes after launch, the rocket has burned through a=
 huge portion of its fuel. This means it has <em>lost</em> mass as that fue=
l has been transformed into energy. In addition, the rocket is farther from=
 Earth=E2=80=99s surface. Gravity therefore pulls on it with even <em>less<=
/em> force. Both the rocket=E2=80=99s mass and its weight have dropped. The=
 rocket=E2=80=99s engines can now push the rocket even faster than they cou=
ld at launch. (Next time you watch a rocket launch, notice how huge those l=
aunch engines are!)</p>

			</div> <!-- /.rich-text -->

		=09
<footer class=3D"article-footer__wrapper___eChRS article-footer__with-sideb=
ar___9oDuK">
=09
=09
<section class=3D"article-footer__power-words___V5fm0" id=3D"power-words" d=
ata-component=3D"print-power-words">
	<header class=3D"article-footer__pw-header___cii2S">
		<h3 class=3D"article-footer__pw-heading___-GYtA">
			Power Words		</h3>

		<a class=3D"article-footer__pw-about___D7W9R" href=3D"https://www.snexplo=
res.org/power-words-aid-stem-literacy/">More About Power Words</a>

		<button type=3D"button" class=3D"article-footer__print-power-words-btn___=
NnOdr print-power-words-btn"></button>
	</header>

	<div class=3D"power-words-container">
		<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>density</strong>: The measure of how condensed some&nbsp;object =
is, found by dividing its mass by its volume.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>element</strong>: A building block of some larger structure. (in=
 chemistry) Each of more than one hundred substances for which the smallest=
 unit of each is a single atom. Examples include hydrogen, oxygen, carbon, =
lithium and uranium.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>engine</strong>: A machine designed to convert energy into usefu=
l mechanical motion. Sometimes an engine is called a motor.&nbsp;(in comput=
er science) A computer program that performs a particular, narrow range of =
functions.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>force</strong>: Some outside influence that can change the motio=
n of a body, hold bodies close to one another, or produce motion or stress =
in a stationary body.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>fuel</strong>: Any material that will release energy during a co=
ntrolled chemical or nuclear reaction. Fossil fuels (coal, natural gas and =
petroleum) are a common type that liberate their energy through chemical re=
actions that take place when heated (usually to the point of burning).</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>fundamental</strong>: Something that is basic or serves as the f=
oundation for another thing or idea.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>gravity</strong>: The force that attracts anything with mass, or=
 bulk, toward any other thing with mass. The more mass that something has, =
the greater its gravity.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>International Space Station</strong>: An artificial satellite th=
at orbits Earth. Run by the United States and Russia, this station provides=
 a research laboratory from which scientists can conduct experiments in bio=
logy, physics and astronomy =E2=80=94 and make observations of Earth.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Jupiter</strong>: (in astronomy) The solar system=E2=80=99s larg=
est planet, it has the shortest day length (9 hours, 55 minutes). A gas gia=
nt, its low density indicates that this planet is composed mostly of the li=
ght elements hydrogen and helium. This planet also releases more heat than =
it receives from the sun as gravity compresses its mass (and slowly shrinks=
 the planet).</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>mass</strong>: A number that shows how much an object resists sp=
eeding up and slowing down =E2=80=94 basically a measure of how much matter=
 that object is made from.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>matter</strong>: Something that occupies space and has mass. Any=
thing on Earth with matter will have a property described as "weight."</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>moon</strong>: The natural satellite of any planet.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>orbit</strong>: The curved path of a celestial object or spacecr=
aft around a galaxy, star, planet or moon. One complete circuit around a ce=
lestial body.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>planet</strong>: A large celestial object that orbits a star but=
 unlike a star does not generate any visible light.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>rocket</strong>: Something propelled into the air or through spa=
ce, sometimes as a weapon of war. A rocket usually is lofted by the release=
 of exhaust gases as some fuel burns. (v.) Something that flings into space=
 at high speed as if fueled by combustion.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>system</strong>: A network of parts that together work to achiev=
e some function. For instance, the blood, vessels and heart are primary com=
ponents of the human body's circulatory system. Similarly, trains, platform=
s, tracks, roadway signals and overpasses are among the potential component=
s of a nation's railway system. System can even be applied to the processes=
 or ideas that are part of some method or ordered set of procedures for get=
ting a task done.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>unit</strong>: (in measurements) A unit of measurement is a stan=
dard way of expressing a physical quantity. Units of measure provide contex=
t for what numerical values represent and so convey the magnitude of physic=
al properties. Examples include inches, kilograms, ohms, gauss, decibels, k=
elvins and nanoseconds.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->	</div>
</section>

